[start section id="20112"]

Mr. Mccormick underwent radical surgery in June of 2010 for his local tumor recurrence as well as the liver metastases.  He is still recovering from the aftermath of the surgery.  Unfortunately, I was not able to see the CT scans obtained today, but I do not anticipate any signs of early tumor recurrence.  The patient's tumor marker CEA is now normalized after surgery.
From my perspective, I would normally recommend an additional six cycles of modified FOLFOX6 as adjuvant therapy.  However, the patient is not in physical shape yet to start treatment.  If he can get back on his feet within the next four weeks, he might be a candidate for additional cycles of chemotherapy.  Otherwise, I would just watch the situation and follow the patient closely with scans every three-months for the first three years after the surgery.
Mr. Mccormick was content with the information received.  All questions were answered.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: Yes, on file at Saint Luke Hospital.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

[end section id="20112"]

